Three banks and two firms have approached the Federal High Court in Lagos for orders and injunctions towards recovering an alleged $91.4 million debt from Benin Electricity Distribution Company (BEDC) Plc and its chairman Victor Osibodu and his wife/director Funke. The counter-claimants/applicants in a suit marked FHC/L/CS/239/2022 before Justice Yellim Bogoro  are Stanbic-IBTC, Fidelity Bank Plc, Keystone Bank Limited, ALM Consulting Limited and Stanbic-IBTC Trustees Limited. Vigeo Holdings Limited (In receivership), VHL International Limited, Global Utilities Management Company Limited, Design Innovation Limited, Mr. Victor Gbolade Sobodu, Mrs. Funke Iyabo Sobodu, Vigeo Power Limited and Benin Electricity Distribution Company (BEDC) Plc are the respondents. Responding to The Nation‘s enquiry on the company’s response to the suit, one Mr. Ibe, who spoke for BEDC on March 15, pleaded for time.   Elegushi urges prayers for Nigeria     ‘Nigeria needs professional care services’     Pupils get free educational materials   “I will revert before noon tomorrow (March 16),” Ibe said, but he did not respond to The Nation‘s reminder at 5:14pm on March 16 and was yet to do so as of the time of filing this report yesterday. The counter-claimants/applicants in their motion on notice are asking the court for an order entering summary judgment against the respondents on the “undisputed principal amount/credit facilities availed by first to third applicants and absence of conceivable and/or sustainable defence to applicants’ Counter-Claim”. They incude $22,300 million (principal sum/restructured credit facility as at March 24, 2016), $55,309,439.13 as of June 5, 2018, N24,785,319 as of June 16 2021 and “judgment in the aggregate/cumulative sum of $77,609,439.13 and N24,785,319 billion, and interest on the above-stated sums at the rate of 12.5 per cent per annum from the date of the judgment till liquidation of the judgment sums”. They also asked the court for an order setting down for trial, the determination of the extent of the Respondents’ indebtedness on the accrued Interest of the stated principal sums from the date of the restructured facilities being March 2, 2016, 5 June 2018 and June 16, 2021, till the date the summary judgment above was entered; being the crux of the Respondents’ alleged dispute. The counter-claimants/applicants also asked the court for an interlocutory order granting leave to them and the Receiver/Manager – Mr. Kunle Ogunba (SAN) – appointed pursuant to a Deed of Appointment of Receiver/Manager dated February 2022 and duly registered at the Corporate Affairs Commission (CAC).